  "prompt": "Which laptop is best for students?",
  "response": "Choosing the best laptop for students depends on several factors, including the student's major, budget, and specific needs (like portability, battery life, and software requirements). Here are some top recommendations across different categories:\n\n### General Recommendations for Students:\n\n1. **Apple MacBook Air (M2)**\n   - **Pros**: Lightweight, excellent battery life, high build quality, macOS ecosystem.\n   - **Cons**: Higher price point.\n\n2. **Dell XPS 13**\n   - **Pros**: Sleek design, stunning display, powerful performance.\n   - **Cons**: Can be pricey with higher configurations.\n\n3. **HP Envy x360**\n   - **Pros**: Convertible design, good performance, affordable compared to other premium models.\n   - **Cons**: Battery life can vary depending on use.\n\n4. **Acer Aspire 5**\n   - **Pros**: Great value for performance, decent battery life, lightweight.\n   - **Cons**: Build quality may not be as premium as others.\n\n5. **Lenovo IdeaPad 5**\n   - **Pros**: Affordable, solid performance, good keyboard.\n   - **Cons**: Design is not as polished.\n\n### Budget Options:\n\n1. **Chromebook (e.g., Acer Chromebook 14)**\n   - **Pros**: Affordable, great battery life, ideal for web-based applications.\n   - **Cons**: Limited offline functionality, depends heavily on internet access.\n\n2. **ASUS VivoBook 15**\n   - **Pros**: Budget-friendly, decent performance for everyday tasks.\n   - **Cons**: Heavier than some ultrabooks.\n\n### High-Performance Needs:\n\n1. **Microsoft Surface Laptop 5**\n   - **Pros**: Premium build quality, great display, runs Windows 11 smoothly.\n   - **Cons**: More expensive; battery life can be average depending on usage.\n\n2. **Razer Blade Stealth 13 (for Gaming/Heavy Computing)**\n   - **Pros**: Powerful hardware, good for gaming and high-performance tasks.\n   - **Cons**: Pricey, battery life can be less optimal.\n\n### Considerations:\n\n- **Battery Life**: Essential for long classes or studying in a library.\n- **Weight and Portability**: A lighter laptop is easier to carry around campus.\n- **Performance**: Consider what software you'll need. For basic tasks (web browsing, word processing), lower specs are fine, but for programming or graphic design, you may need a more powerful machine.\n- **Operating System**: Choose between macOS, Windows, or Chrome OS based on your preferences and software requirements.\n\nIn summary, a well-rounded laptop like the Apple MacBook Air or Dell XPS 13 suits many students, while Chromebooks are great for those on a budget or primarily using web-based applications. Always consider your individual needs before making a decision!",
